text: I find this movie really interesting, and would definitely watch it. To all of those people who think that the main character's actions are exaggerated, let me say that I had experienced the same pain of losing a dog to a criminal.  It was back in 2012 when some bastards robbed my home. They decided to poison my dog, and best friend who wasn't even half a metre tall and in the back yard. Back then I was in high school, things had gotten rough, and he would be the only one that I trusted to tell my worries to. At first I thought it was a cold because he whimpered slightly at first, and then into yelps on the second day. I could see that he was in pain, and unfortunately, he had to be put down. Which broke my heart, seeing that he suffered so much, adding to the fact that I wasn't there for him when he died because I was forced to go to school.  I am a really quiet person at school, everyone thinks that I'm all shy and distant. However, even 2 years on, I still do not forgive the person who did that to him. If I ever found out, I would gouge their eyes out slowly,then pour acid down his throat so he knew how my dog felt in his final days. I would seriously make them pay for the pain they had caused on my dog and I. However, I do not know who did it, and the police are useless at finding the criminal. So Im holding on to the hope that there is an afterlife, and I can deal with them there.

Yes it's an action movie, but it is self-conscious of that : if you paid to go see this movie expecting an intelligent or some metaphysical plot, you're obviously not very smart.  See the movie for what it's worth and what it seeks to be : an action movie marking the return of Keanu Reeves.

text: Just saw this, it was pretty great. Started very slow, and the atmosphere was a little weird at the beginning. Early on I even caught myself thinking "Man, this movie sucks. I could be watching Fury or something else instead." Even the initial conflict that sparks everything else in the movie was kind of shallow and dumb, but boy, once the action started this movie won me over. It's just so cool. A lot of the action was very reminiscent of, say, John Woo Hong Kong action flicks with lots of gunplay. Keanu pulls off the stone cold badass pretty well. Some of his lines were a bit awkward, but overall good job. I actually don't remember him talking all that much in the movie, so that might have helped a bit. Michael Nyqvist was god damn fantastic. He was very likable for an antagonist. I would definitely watch this movie again. However, it's not for everyone. I remember a couple walking out of the movie about halfway in, and that was even after the movie started getting good.Â

text: I really enjoyed this movie. Sure, you could nitpick but the action sequences are great with a super slick, graceful feel to them, the car is badass, and the movie does have a sense of humor about itself. The best part is the story world. New York City is dark, highly polished with tones of grey. The assassins had their own slang ("dinner reservations), code of conduct ("house rules"), and currency ("gold coin"). Watching Keanu navigate his way through that world was a lot of fun. From the cops ("You working again?) to the clean up crew ("it's good to see you again, John"), to Continental Hotel ("sorry about the, uh, disturbance last night, Mr. Wick").

text: He is a good actor and the movie was entertaining but not near as good as it could have been. A good actor can have flops just as easy as successes because of weak characters, bad plot or lousy script dialogue (got to have those good lines. The best Clint Eastwood type of line in the movie...when the priest says he can't open the vault because Viggo will kill him...and John Wick's reply..."uh huh"). A lot of dark scenes and too much gun play. This was like a Steven Seagal flick. Superman beats all opposition. Usually a boring story.Â  Interesting characters: puppy, Viggo, Marcus, Ms. Perkins (like Gina Carano in "haywire" or another female hit woman in "four assassins"), hotel manager, and I think the other was Winston (where they surrounded Ms. Perkins and finished her).Â  A good movie needs more elements than good charisma, action, and some interesting characters. The plot was too straightforward. The intro to why Wick goes after Viggo's son is a weak plot intro. Like figure the odds of stealing a car from one of his father's former hitman associates. Could have been a better intro reason. The puppy was a good touch. They wasted the idea too soon though.Â  Wife has cancer...from movie with Charlize Theron. Sending the bouncer home was like something from a Chuck Norris flick. Killing the dog was "shooter"...Mark Wahlberg...and a much better movie. The overall plot reminded me a lot of Jason Statham movies. The hero needs to know how to escape to safety like a commando (like the escape seen in "the Transporter" when the house is blown up and they go down a shaft into the ocean...not just gung ho every time. This movie just didn't have the "smarts" in the plot.Â  Keanu Reeves at least made it watchable.Â

text: To the people trashing this film and the main character's motivation: Actually watch the movie before you decide to criticize it so you don't make yourself look foolish. He doesn't go after the bad guys simply because they killed his dog. That would be stupid as he could easily replace it and never have to deal with that criminal underworld again. He goes after them because before his wife died from a terminal illness she arranged for the dog to be given to John as a gift to help in the grieving process. So he wouldn't have to face it alone and he'd have something to love. I'm sure if you people had the only person you love taken from you, and someone destroyed that person's last gift to you, you would be ready to kill droves of gangsters as well.
